<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06220114 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06220114 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MEDICAL; HEALTH; DISEASE; WEATHER; CAUSE; PREVENTION; PRODUCT; REPORT; CANCER;RESEARCH  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Sun protection factors, or SPFs, in sunscreen products may not block enough ofthe sun's truly harmful rays to help wearers avoid skin damage, a Pennsylvaniastudy says.;    A study of seven sunscreens found no difference in the amountof protection offered by a sunscreen with an SPF of 4 and one with an SPF of30 when the researchers looked at how they blocked one type of the sun'sdamaging rays, the researchers wrote in the August issue of the Journal of theAmerican Academy of Dermatology.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STUDY QUESTIONS SUNSCREEN PROTECTIONDAMAGING RAYS COULD GET THROUGH  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     SPF measurements;  SPFs are numerical measures of the amount of protectionthat a sunscreen offers from the sun's rays, which include ultraviolet B andultraviolet A.;    Both types of the rays, known as UVA and UVB, can damagethe skin and promote cancer, according to the Skin Cancer Foundation.;    Noneof the sunscreens with SPFs over 4 provided any additional protection againstUVA rays, according to the study.;    &quot;This is contrary to the common beliefthat sunscreens with increasing SPF must block more UVA,&quot; wrote Dr. Kays H.Kaidbey of the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania.;    UVA rays notblocked well;  One sunscreen studied with an SPF of 4 actually only protectedlike a sunscreen with an SPF of 1.6 when the researchers looked at how itblocked UVA rays.;    And when the researchers studied another sunscreen withan SPF of 30, they found that it also provided a UVA protection factor of1.6.;    Chronic sun exposure causes wrinkling, coarsening, splotches and aloss of skin elasticity and may lead to skin cancer, according to the SkinCancer Foundation.;    The sun's rays also have been linked to the increasingincidence of malignant melanoma in the United States, which is growing fasterthan any other cancer, according to the American Cancer Society.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Medical Tribune News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910807  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  300  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday August 7, 199100220114,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>